{{geology-stub}}

The '''anacoustic zone''', also known as the zone of silence, is the region of the [[atmosphere of Earth]] above about {{convert|160|km|mi|sp=us}} where the [[air density]] becomes so low that air molecules are not close enough to support transmission of [[sound]] waves within the hearing range.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.daviddarling.info/encyclopedia/A/anacoustic_zone.html | title = Anacoustic zone}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=dt7ow1Af86YC&pg=PA18 | page = 18 | title = The complete book of spaceflight: from Apollo 1 to zero gravity | isbn = 978-0-471-05649-2 | author1 = Darling, David | author2 = Darling, David J | year = 2003}}</ref>
As altitude increases through the atmosphere, the first sound waves to disappear are the high pitched, high-frequency (short wavelength) ones. At a certain altitude (roughly {{convert|160|km|mi|sp=us}}) even the lowest frequency tone that can be heard by a human being (around 20&nbsp;Hz) no longer can be transmitted.
With increasing height, the atmosphere becomes more rarefied, which increases the mean time between collisions of molecules (also known as [[Mean free time]]). The maximum frequency a sound wave can have and still be able to propagate in a gas is roughly the inverse of the mean free time<ref>{{cite web|title=Is there an upper frequency limit to ultrasound?|url=http://physics.stackexchange.com/questions/23418/is-there-an-upper-frequency-limit-to-ultrasound|publisher=stackexchange.com|accessdate=20 October 2013}}</ref> (molecular [[mean free path]] divided by average molecular speed). Hence the more rarefied a gas medium, the lower is the cut-off frequency for sound propagation in that medium.
