'''Paul Brooks''' (1909–1998) was a nature writer, book editor, and environmentalist.<ref name=WaldenOrg>{{cite web|postscript=; collection processed, December 2014, by Chloe Morse-Harding|title=Paul Brooks papers, 10 April 1852 - 12 December 1998, The Paul Brooks Collection|website=The Walden Woods Project (walden.org)|url=https://www.walden.org/work/the-paul-brooks-collection-a-finding-aid/}}</ref>
Born in New York City, Paul Brooks received in 1931 his bachelor's degree from Harvard University, where he was the editor of the [[Harvard Lampoon]].<ref name=WaldenOrg/> Soon after graduation, he became an employee at the publishing company [[Houghton Mifflin]] in Boston and remained with the company for 40 years. He was editor-in-chief of Houghton Mifflin's General Book Department from 1943 until his retirement in 1969. He wrote ''Two Park Street: A Publishing Memoir'', containing anecdotes about his experiences editing the works of [[Rachel Carson]], [[Roger Tory Peterson]], [[Winston Churchill]], [[Arthur Schlesinger Jr.]], and [[James Agee]], among others.<ref>{{cite web|title=Review of ''Two Park Street'' by Paul Brooks|website=Publishers Weekly|date=1 December 1986|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-395-37774-1}}</ref> Paul Brooks suggested the title ''Silent Spring'' for Rachel Carson's famous book.<ref>{{cite book|title=And No Birds Sing: Rhetorical Analyses of Rachel Carson's Silent Spring|editor=Waddell, Craig|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HzvI1hotILUC&pg=PR15|year=2000|publisher=Southern Illinois University Press|pages=xv–xvi}}</ref>
In addition to his career as an editor, Brooks was also a prolific author of books and articles. He won the 1965 [[John Burroughs Medal]] for his 1964 book ''Roadless Area''.
{{blockquote|A passionate environmental activist, Brooks traveled extensively with his wife, Susan (Susie), and took leadership roles in numerous organizations, such as the [[Sierra Club]] and [[Massachusetts Audubon Society]]. He was asked to lecture all over the United States throughout his career.<ref name=WaldenOrg/>}}
==Books== *{{cite book|title=Roadless Area|year=1964|location=New York|publisher=Knopf|postscript=; 259 pages}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Review of ''Roadless Area'' by Paul Brooks|date=|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/paul-brooks-3/roadless-area/|website=Kirkus Reviews}}</ref> *{{cite book|title=The Pursuit of Wilderness|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|year=1971|postscript=; 220 pages}}<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Oryx|volume=11|issue=4|title=Review of ''The Pursuit of Wilderness, by Paul Brooks|date=January 1972|page=288|author=Smith, Anthony|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/oryx/article/pursuit-of-wilderness-by-brooks-paul-houghton-mifflin-695-roadless-area-by-brooks-paul-ballantyne-40p-nameless-valleys-shining-mountains-by-milton-john-p-walker-750/B10CB70E8A79AFD7E8AEB8FA3507F39A}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Review of ''The Pursuit of Wilderness'' by Paul Brooks|date=17 May 1971|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/paul-brooks-6/the-pursuit-of-wilderness-2/|website=Kirkus Reviews}}</ref> *{{cite book|title=The House of Life: Rachel Carson at Work|location=Boston|publisher=G. K. Hall|year=1972}}<ref>{{cite newspaper|author=Johnson, Josephine|authorlink=Josephine Johnson|title=Review of ''The House of Life: Rachel Carson at Work'' by Paul Brooks|newspaper=NY Times|date=30 April 1972|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1972/04/30/archives/the-house-of-life-rachel-carson-at-work-by-paul-brooks-illustrated.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Review of ''The House of Life: Rachel Carson at Work'' by Paul Brooks|date=13 March 1972|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/paul-brooks/the-house-of-life-rachel-carson-at-work/|website=Kirkus Reviews}}</ref> *{{cite book|title=The View from Lincoln Hill: Man and the Land in a New England Town|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|year=1976|postscript=; 273 pages}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Review of ''The View from Lincoln Hill: Man and the Land in a New England Town'' by Paul Brooks|date=6 August 1976|url=https://www.